What is a host's name?

I have found myself in the middle of a debate concerning interpretation of
the various standards concerning host names and such as applied to the
MILNET.

It has been my understanding that a host's name is that which appears in the
master table at the NIC or in the domain database.  However, another host,
from which our hosts need to receive mail, and its administrator believe
that "The '.ARPA' is NOT part of your host's node name!  It's only required
to find you host's address." This host in its SMTP session with our hosts
sends RCPT lines of &lt;user@name-without-the-dot-arpa&gt;, and, as our hosts no
longer know any non-domain style names since the end of March purge of the
NIC host tables, our hosts refuse the mail with a 550 Host "name" Unknown.

The simple way to make things work would be to modify our local copies of
the host tables to add our hosts' names stripped of the .ARPA so that they
will accept mail sent by the other host without the .ARPA in the RCPT line.
The negative side of this is that our hosts' mail system will then permit
users to send mail using the non-domain style name.

Where is the authoritative answer to this question?

Please reply to domain-question@bbncc-eur.arpa and I will sumarize 
the responses.

Thanks.

--- Larry Kaufman
    lkaufman@bbncc-eur.arpa
    BBNCC, MILNET Technical Support Engineer

